  "term": "thm:quotient-rule",
  "kind": "Theorem",
  "title": "Quotient Rule",
  "root": "",
  "statement": "Let $A \\subseteq \\mathbb{R}$, let $f, g : A \\to \\mathbb{R}$, and let $c \\in A$ be a limit point of $A$. Suppose that $f$ and $g$ are differentiable at $c$ and that $g(c) \\neq 0$. Then $f/g$ is differentiable at $c$, and\n\\[\n\\left(\\frac{f}{g}\\right)'(c) = \\frac{f'(c)g(c) - f(c)g'(c)}{(g(c))^2}.\n\\]",
